'''Marchinha''' ({{IPA-pt|maɾˈʃiɲɐ}}, also called "marchinha de carnaval", "marchinha carnavalesca" or "marcha carnavalesca) is one of several genres of music typical of [[Brazilian Carnival]] in [[Rio de Janeiro]] and [[Southeast Region, Brazil|Southeast Region of Brazil]]. The other main carnival genres are: [[samba-enredo]], [[frevo]], [[maracatu]] and [[Axé music]].

Marchinha is an extremely comic genre of music and the very name "marchinha" (little march) satirizes the seriousness of [[march (music)|military marches]], in both the musical and step senses, which are involved in the generalised satirization of the society that occurs during the carnival, for example the election of [[King Momo (Carnival character)|Rei Momo]] (King Momo, the king of carnival). The bands features [[trombone]]s, [[tuba]]s, [[French horn|horn]]s, [[clarinet]]s, [[flute]]s and [[piccolo]]s and [[percussion]].

The first marchinha was the composition (in 1899) of [[Chiquinha Gonzaga]] entitled "O Abre Alas", made to the [[Cordão Carnavalesco]] "Rosa de Outro".<ref>[https://archive.is/20070704161038/http://www.dicionariompb.com.br/detalhe.asp?nome=Chiquinha+Gonzaga&tabela=T_FORM_A&qdetalhe=art], Dicionário Cravo Albin</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.vidaslusofonas.pt/chiquinha_gonzaga.htm |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-09-28 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020144521/http://www.vidaslusofonas.pt/chiquinha_gonzaga.htm |archivedate=2011-10-20 |df= }}</ref>

Marchinhas are composed and played to date by the [[Carnival block|blocos carnavalescos]] every year, in the "street carnival" of Rio de Janeiro.

