{{Infobox video game | title = Solstice Chronicles: MIA | image = File:Solsticechrmiagame.jpg | caption = | developer = [[Ironward]] | publisher = | director = | producer = | designer = | programmer = | artist = | writer = Hrvoje Horvatek | composer = | series = | engine = [[Unreal Engine]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows]] | released = <!-- {{Video game release|}} --> | genre = [[Top-down perspective|Top-down]], [[3D computer graphics|3-D]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] }}
'''''Solstice Chronicles: MIA''''' is a [[Isometric graphics in video games and pixel art|isometric]] sci-fi shooter video game, developed by [[Ironward]] and published by Nkidu Games inc. for [[Microsoft Windows]]. The game was released on July 26, 2017 on [[Steam (software)|Steam]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.goodgame.hr/solstice-chronicles-mia/|title=Solstice Chronicles: MIA - GoodGame.hr|website=www.goodgame.hr}}</ref> It is a spinoff of the previous game [[The Red Solstice]]. It is a [[twin-stick shooter]], inspired by games such as [[Alien Shooter]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://adria.ign.com/solstice-chronicles-mia/10212/preview/zaigrali-smo-solstice-chronicles-mia|title=Zaigrali smo Solstice Chronicles: MIA!|date=15 November 2016|publisher=}}</ref>
The story is described "In a dead colony, a corporate marine is left far behind enemy lines. With an unlikely help of an insurgent drone, he faces the battle for survival against an army of murderous, mindless mutants... and worse things".
The single-player campaign is focused on a marine called Grunt and his drone, stranden on the planet of [[Mars]].
==Reception== ''The Red Solstice'' received mixed reviews upon release. The game currently holds 68% on [[Metacritic]] based on 12 reviews.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/solstice-chronicles-mia|title=Solstice Chronicles: MIA|website=Metacritic}}</ref> The reviewing site GameCritics praised the game stating "Solstice Chronicles: MIA is a breath of fresh air in the twin-stick shooter genre. The threat system makes it feel like nothing else out there, transforming it from just another run-and-gun into something far more strategic and complex. It’s not a complete success, but it manages to add a satisfying amount of strategy without skimping on the action, which is a feat that I’m shocked no one has managed before."<ref>{{cite web|url=https://gamecritics.com/daniel-weissenberger/solstice-chronicles-mia-review/|title=Solstice Chronicles: MIA Review – GameCritics.com|website=gamecritics.com}}</ref> On the other hand, ZTGD was less positive, criticizing the absence of co-op and the rough edges of the game, as well as the bad storyline.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ztgd.com/solstice-chronicles-mia/review/|title=Solstice Chronicles: MIA (PC) Review|date=1 August 2017|publisher=}}</ref>
